Implementation details:

def _find_line_start(f, pos):
    if pos == 0:
        return 0
    f.seek(pos)
    # if current char is newline, line starts after it
    if f.read(1) == b'\n':
        return pos + 1
    # else move back until newline or start
    while pos > 0:
        pos -= 1
        f.seek(pos)
        if f.read(1) == b'\n':
            return pos + 1
    return 0

def _read_line(f, start):
    f.seek(start)
    line_bytes = bytearray()
    while True:
        b = f.read(1)
        if not b or b == b'\n':
            break
        line_bytes.extend(b)
    return bytes(line_bytes)

But we need to return byte offset of line start (or insertion point). In binary search loop:

low = 0
high = file_size
while low < high:
    mid = (low + high) // 2
    line_start = find_line_start(f, mid)
    line = read_line(f, line_start)
    if line < target:
        low = line_start + len(line) + 1  # skip newline
    else:
        high = line_start
return low

Edge Cases: If line is empty (i.e., two consecutive newlines) treat line as empty bytes.

Need to handle file may not end with newline; last line may not have newline. In that case, when we compute line_start + len(line) + 1 may go beyond file size if no newline. Better: after reading line, we can find line_end: we can seek to line_start, read until newline or EOF, then get position after reading (i.e., current file pointer). So we can compute line_end = f.tell() after reading line (which will be at newline or EOF). Then if we need to skip line, low = line_end.

